    "body": "### Neovim version (nvim -v)\r\n\r\nNVIM v0.8.0\r\n\r\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\r\n\r\nyes, vim 9.0.217\r\n\r\n### Operating system/version\r\n\r\nmacOS 12.6\r\n\r\n### Terminal name/version\r\n\r\nkitty 0.26.4\r\n\r\n### $TERM environment variable\r\n\r\nxterm-kitty\r\n\r\n### Installation\r\n\r\nHomebrew\r\n\r\n### How to reproduce the issue\r\n\r\n1. Ensure you have a SourceCodePro font installed and configured as the current font in kitty. I use SauceCodePro Nerd Font, but this should be reproducible with other SourceCodePro fonts.\r\nMinimal kitty.conf:\r\n```\r\nfont_family SauceCodePro Nerd Font\r\ndisable_ligatures always\r\n```\r\n2. `nvim --clean`\r\n3. `:set listchars+=space:Â·`\r\n4. `:set list`\r\n5. Insert `l l` text into a document\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\nThe font should render with no ligatures.\r\n\r\n### Actual behavior\r\n\r\n\"lÂ·l\" replaces the first \"l\" while displaying.\r\n<img width=\"196\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2022-10-27 at 14 52 10\" src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1916568/198395590-eebc2c37-0930-4d87-9460-4a89276c1eab.png\">\r\n\r\nVSCode had this same issue - https://github.com/microsoft/vscode/issues/106583 \r\n\r\nIt looks like they solved it by inserting a U+200C ZERO WIDTH NON-JOINER character before and after each whitespace character. That's not an option with listchars because space must be a single character.\r\n\r\nI was able to work around this by disabling ccmp in my kitty.conf:\r\n```\r\nfont_features SauceCodeProNerdFontComplete-Regular -ccmp\r\n```",
